 [
  {
    "nodeId": "Finding_River_Leads_OOP",
    "quizType": "anki",
    "question": "Finding Leads OOP with Strong Hands when your Opponent Lacks Bluffs",
    "answer": "<h2>Consider Leading the River When</h2><ul><li>Villain has a non-polarized range that is SD heavy and significantly lacks air combos AND</li><li>Your hand is worth more than a check AND</li><li>Your range can support betting</li></ul> <p>SRP BvB: 2c3c4c xc 6d xc 6c CAN LEAD</p> <p>SRP MPvsBB: 8c6c9s D33 R50 C 3h B70 C 4c LEAD ALL IN </p> <p>4B BTNvsBB: Jd5h2c B20 C 3d B25 C 5s CANT LEAD</p> <p>Do <b>NOT</b> use this play when opponent has a polar turn range containing many <b>non-SD bluffs</b> that will shove river when we check.</p>"
  },
  {
    "nodeId": "Calling_vs_Polarization",
    "quizType": "anki",
    "question": "Calling vs Polarization",
    "answer": "<h2>Vs Aggressive Polarization</h2><ul><li><b>FOLD</b> all of your <b>bluffcatchers vs weak/tight</b> regs - only find calls against aggressive regs and players who are capable of bluffing!</li><li>Against, players who x/R with proper aggression <b>sometimes</b> you should <b>x-back strong hands IP</b> that don't want to see a x/r and barrel.</li><li>First <b>consider what they are representing</b> - then try to call with hands that <b>block their value</b></li></ul>"
  },
  {
    "nodeId": "Facing_4Bet_OOP_Splitting_Raise_Ranges",
    "quizType": "anki",
    "question": "Facing 4Bet OOP: Splitting X/R Ranges into Small/Big Sizes. How to do it?",
    "answer": "<p>Facing a 4Bet OOP is not a great node. Once we face a 4B we shift from a high-EV 3B spot to one where we just want to lose as little as possible.</p><h2>Donking</h2><p>Having a Donking Range Makes Sense When</p><ul><li>Your cold call range has flopped multiple sets</li><li>Your opponent is likely check back (AK combos have missed the board)</li><li>Your hand class has a clear answer vs raise<ul><li>Don't lead lots of equity hands</li><li>Don't lead complete trash</li></ul></li></ul><h2>Splitting X/R Ranges into Small/Big Sizes</h2><ul><li>Even at low SPRs, OOP should have a raising range vs small (likely range) cbets</li><li>First, define the bottom of your value bet range - then choose your bluffs<ul><li>Avoid hands that suffer vs shove</li></ul></li><li>Generally you want to have an all-in size and a small size <ul><li>All-in range should be draws that want to capitalize on their fold equity plus value hands that need protection</li></ul></li><li>You can almost always shove an 8-out draw or better</li></ul><h2>Make sure you play your range and NOT your specific hand vs regs</h2><ul><li>If the flop checks around and the turn is good for your opponent, don't get too excited with a big hand and leave your checking range unprotected<ul><li>Check shove highest equity draws</li><li>Slowplay your best value hands</li></ul></li></ul><h2>Try to identify spots where the pool doesn't understand their hand's equity vs a range with thin value raises</h2><ul><li>The wider your opponent's range, the better</li><li>The more sizing tell you can pick up, the better</li><li>The more loosely they call, the better</li><li>The more they cbet too weak a range, the better</li></ul>"   
  },
